00230 /* the basis for a Node tree, all links and nodes reside internal here */
00231 /* only re-usable node trees are in the library though, materials and textures allocate own tree struct */
00232 typedef struct bNodeTree {
00233     ID id;
00234     struct AnimData *adt;       /* animation data (must be immediately after id for utilities to use it) */ 
00235     
00236     struct bGPdata *gpd;        /* grease pencil data */
00237     
00238     ListBase nodes, links;
00239     
00240     int type, init;                 /* set init on fileread */
00241     int cur_index;                  /* sockets in groups have unique identifiers, adding new sockets always 
00242                                      * will increase this counter */
00243     int flag;
00244     int update;                     /* update flags */
00245     
00246     int nodetype;                   /* specific node type this tree is used for */
00247     
00248     ListBase inputs, outputs;       /* external sockets for group nodes */
00249     
00250     /* execution data */
00251     /* XXX It would be preferable to completely move this data out of the underlying node tree,
00252      * so node tree execution could finally run independent of the tree itself. This would allow node trees
00253      * to be merely linked by other data (materials, textures, etc.), as ID data is supposed to.
00254      * Execution data is generated from the tree once at execution start and can then be used
00255      * as long as necessary, even while the tree is being modified.
00256      */
00257     struct bNodeTreeExec *execdata;
00258     
00259     /* callbacks */
00260     void (*progress)(void *, float progress);
00261     void (*stats_draw)(void *, char *str);
00262     int (*test_break)(void *);
00263     void *tbh, *prh, *sdh;
00264     
00265 } bNodeTree;
